6 THINGS I WSH I COULD TELL EVERYBODY BEFORE THEY START GETTING IN SHAPE....

Thinking back on when my fitness journey started there are a lot of things that I wish I knew.

I could have avoided feeling burnt out and confused at some points.

Like, back in the day when I used to SLAM down whey protein shakes right before a workout and wonder why I felt so sick of you hours later ğŸ˜‚

I was following what everyone else was doing and It took me a while to figure out that dairy just doesn't work well with me.... and that it takes a while to digest protein.

No one is perfect though and it is definitely better to start sooner than later.

These few pointers worth being reminded of...

1) Be grateful for your all of your progress. Get inspired by others without being envious. Do the work to love your body, as cliche as it sounds. This will help you avoid neglecting yourself into a cycle of giving up and starting all over.

2) You don't need intense workouts to get results. You need to learn to challenge yourself and follow the right strategy.

3) Getting clear on why you want to is the most important piece. Your mindset matters the most.

4) Whole food is the answer. The closer it is to nature, the better. When you eat well you feel better.

5) Getting in shape is 24/7 investment that requires you to listen to your body... but it's okay to clock out and just enjoy yourself from time to time.

6) It's never too late to start or re-start. Just be consistent when you do and you will go very far.

News Flash - about 1/5 of the global cotton supply comes from Xinjiang China. Allegations that this cotton was produced through forced labour of Uyghurs has worried NGOs, brands, governments and consumers. 

International brands like H&M and Nike have called out against the malpractice and felt the retaliation of China, sending a clear message that brands have no right to get involved in government business. 

But on a political level the issue was used as well by the Trump administration, banning all US brands from sourcing Xinjiang cotton. The problem is that the textile supply chain lacks transparency and it is very difficult to trace the cotton from a t-shirt all the way back to the farm. On top of that cotton prices are skyrocketing all over the world.

In this episode, I am wearing a pair of Air Jordan 1 High Zoom Air CMFT in Black Monarch colorway. I initially thought that these were the continuation of Air Jordan 1 High Zoom line with full-length zoom air units exposed underneath the insoles that has been releasing since 2019. I soon discovered that Air Jordan 1 High Zoom Air CMFT line was a completely new line of sneakers utilizing totally different cushioning setup. Instead of the exposed full-length zoom air, zoom bag is only imbedded in the heel area while the entire bottom is made out of a foam material encapsulated by rubber-trim outsole. Once again, I usually donâ€™t wear my Jordans as soon as I pick them up because I have other 100 plus pairs in my collection waiting to be Un-DS-ed but this pair was different. These went straight to my feet early this year. To showcase how versatile this particular sneakers are for all ages, AJ1 High Zoom Air CMFT Black Monarch were put together with sable color long-sleeve t-shirt from Lululemon along with black dress pants from Giorgio Armani. Finally, overall style is further accentuated with a black sports jacket from Emporio Armani.

A long-forgotten and rare Hip-Hop album by Kobe Bryant has been leaked 21 years after it was recorded back in the year 2000. The project, aptly titled â€˜Kobe Bryant LPâ€™, is considered a relic from the past, as only a few of its tracks had been published.

The full album was leaked, including 16 tracks with a runtime of 1 hour 1 minute. Kobe proves in the disc that he was a pretty capable rapper, and that Shaq wasnâ€™t the only Laker who was able to drop some bars, but the most surprising aspect of the album is the amount of star power that Kobe got for the features. 

Nas, 50 Cent, Destinyâ€™s Child were among the amazing featured artists, and even other solid artists from the time like Black Though and Beanie Sigel make an appearance. Supermodel Tyra Banks and battle rapped Broady Boy round out the guest list. 

Kobeâ€™s sound is fascinating because he doesnâ€™t really sound like an NBA player, or like Kobe Bryant, attempting to make gimmicky rap. Kobe had solid rhymes and schemes, and was ready to go rap in tough situations like street freestyle battles. The success of his NBA career is obvious, but maybe if he needed to rap to earn the bread, he wouldnâ€™t have done half bad. 

At the end of the day, LL Cool J recommended Kobe to drop his rap ambitions and focus on his career. Obviously, that worked out in the end.
